<h1>From Henry Bouquet</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">[Raystown, 3 August 1758]</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I had the pleasure of two Letters from you this morning, and as one of them was upon a most important subject, I read it with great attention, as every thing that has been so seriously considered by you deserves my utmost regard, your arguments are clear, and delivered with that openess and candour that becomes a Gentleman and a Soldier, but give me leave my Dear Sir to answer you in the same stile.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> At the same time that I was favourd with your Letter, I received one from the General, with express Orders to begin to open the road from this place across the Allegeny Mountains,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> and as I shall allwayes oblige the directions
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-05-02-pb-0365">[365]</span>
of a Superiour Officer with readiness, there was no room left to hesitate, In the present case I shall execute them with the greater pleasure, as Col. Burd who is this Moment arrived from Edmund Swamp, Whether he had accompanied Sr John St clair, assures me that a very good Waggon road may be made with ease and speed through the Gap that we have lately discovered,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> and this is the joint opinion of every person who went, they also agree that there are great numbers of fine springs the whole way, and good food for Horses so far as they have yet gone, Sir John went forward this morning, and sent me back word by a person coming from Major Armstrong, that as far as he had gone he found the road good, and every other thing answering our expectations<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> I cannot therefore entertain the least doubt that we shall all now go on hand in hand and that the same zeal for the service that has hitherto been so distinquishing a part of your character will carry you by Reas Town over the Alligeny Mountains to Fort du Quesne</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Draft: a draft of a letter or document in the handwriting of someone other than the author ]">Df</abbr>, British Museum: Add. MSS 21641 (Bouquet Papers).
 For the dating of this letter, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0287&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0002#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0002" class="document">note 2.</a></p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p><a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0283" class="document">GWs letter</a> on a most important subject was that of 2 Aug.<span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ', printed above' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-06]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span>; the second letter has not been identified.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>On 3 Aug. Bouquet wrote Forbes: I received this morning, through Major Halketts letter of July 31, your orders to open the route from here [Raystown] across the mountains immediately (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald H. Kent et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Henry Bouquet&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Harrisburg, Pa., 1951-94. ]">Stevens, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bouquet Papers</span></span>, 2:31214). This seems to confirm that Bouquet wrote this undated draft of a letter to GW on 3 August. During the next three weeks Bouquet employed a number of parties working simultaneously on different segments of a road from Raystown to the site of Loyalhanna on the far side of Laurel Hill, toward which he sent on 23 August a detachment of soldiers and his artillery to begin to build and fortify a new encampment for the army (Bouquet to John St. Clair, 23 Aug., ibid., 4089). Bouquet himself marched with most of his troops from Raystown on 7 Sept. for Loyalhanna.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-05-02-0283&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-05-02-0283-fn-0001#GEWN-02-05-02-0283-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Bouquet, 2 Aug., n.1</a>, for James Burds mission. Edmunds Swamp was across Allegheny Mountain about twenty-five miles from Raystown.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-05-02-0287-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>On 2 Aug. Bouquet got a letter dated the same day from Maj. George Armstrong of the 3d Battalion of the Pennsylvania Regiment, who was encamped on Drounding (Quemahoning) Creek.</p>

</div>
</div>
